WEBVTT

00:04.267 --> 00:05.689
This is July 29, 1987. We're in the dean's 
conference room at Texas A&M. I'm interviewing

00:11.056 --> 00:13.299
Chewie Hinojosa.

00:16.203 --> 00:16.764
OK. I first got involved with Texas A&M University 
back in 1954 when I came here as a student. I was in

00:23.213 --> 00:31.084
general studies at the time and trying to find a 
career or curriculum that would interest me.

00:31.705 --> 00:42.996
During the career day of that year, I was able to 
look around the university and saw that the work in

00:31.705 --> 00:42.996
the Department of Architecture interested me and 
felt that I could do it and enjoy it. Where were you

00:44.477 --> 00:45.738
living at that time? Originally, I came from south 
Texas in the little town of Ed Couch in the lower Rio

00:46.659 --> 00:51.604
Grande Valley. It's about 20 miles from the 
Mexican border and about 50 miles inland from the

00:52.524 --> 00:58.450
Texas Gulf Coast. You were up here for a career day. 
Actually, I was already enrolled at A&M as a

01:00.899 --> 01:06.506
student at the time, yeah. How did that happen? Why 
did you choose A&M? Oh, A&M, yes. Well, my father

01:11.333 --> 01:22.688
talked to a friend of his he knew who had a feet store 
there in Edcouch, and he was an A&M graduate. And so

01:23.191 --> 01:30.822
he asked him if he would suggest any university 
that I might go to after I graduated from high

01:23.191 --> 01:30.822
school, after getting ready to graduate from high 
school. So he, you know, Nagy, he recommended

01:30.842 --> 01:32.945
Texas A&M. He thought it was a good school. And so 
that was how I happened to select A&M, you know. And

01:38.714 --> 01:40.557
then you came up for career day. No. And I just 
applied. to the university at the time. It was a

01:45.830 --> 01:47.433
college, Texas A&M College. Sight unseen. Yes, 
sight unseen, just based on catalogs and whatever

01:49.216 --> 02:01.135
I could get in the mail from them after I decided to 
inquire about the university and decided to come

01:49.216 --> 02:01.135
to A&M. And so they accepted my enrollment based on 
the normal procedures for enrolling. It wasn't

02:07.133 --> 02:13.322
until I was here for about a year, almost a year, 
that I didn't know what to enroll in, basically. I

02:13.382 --> 02:16.186
just enrolled in a general engineering 
curriculum. And after about three quarters of the

02:17.548 --> 02:22.356
year, I wasn't really doing well. And I actually 
was in the Corps for one year. And it was a miserable

02:25.300 --> 02:28.845
experience, because we really couldn't study. 
Yeah. Was it mandated to be in the Corps at that

02:31.469 --> 02:33.512
time? Actually, interestingly enough, at the 
time, A new president had been hired by him who was

02:37.407 --> 02:40.391
not an Aggie. I believe his name was Morgan, 
President Morgan, if I remember correctly. And

02:45.417 --> 02:54.589
he, being, I believe, from the East, had requested 
and had gotten approval to make the Corps optional

02:45.417 --> 02:54.589
at the time. But when I enrolled, since all the 
literature was kind of geared to the Corps, and I

02:55.289 --> 03:02.098
was a member of the Texas National Guard at the 
time, I think it will be something like that. I did

03:04.691 --> 03:10.984
enjoy some discipline and kind of the rigors of the 
military and order and all that. That appealed to

03:11.024 --> 03:11.685
me. But when we landed here in the first weekend 
after we had been here for about a week in

03:12.426 --> 03:20.442
orientation, We lost about 15 or 20 freshmen that 
first weekend because of the crazy, I mean, this is

03:21.080 --> 03:31.556
like, they were going out to West Point, that's 
what they were trying to do. Interestingly

03:31.576 --> 03:45.957
enough, also, I guess part of the psychology was 
that the upperclassmen could not touch us

03:31.576 --> 03:45.957
physically because it had also been mandated that 
you could not touch a student physically,

03:31.576 --> 03:45.957
physically haze them because they had had some 
problems in the past.

03:47.000 --> 03:48.702
And they had some after that, too. Yes. They had 
some brothers afterwards, too. And so they had

03:51.324 --> 03:55.808
given strict orders they would not touch a student 
physically. So they launched a psychological

03:55.828 --> 03:58.571
warfare, which is probably worse. Yeah. Because 
they really, it was a reign of terror on us all the

03:59.372 --> 04:04.817
time, constantly, constantly. And if I remember 
correctly, the numbers out of, I think our outfit

04:05.518 --> 04:09.582
had 120 freshmen. And there were about 60 of us left 
by the middle of the school year. And all of us were

04:15.383 --> 04:19.427
just barely hanging in there grade-wise and so 
forth. And then about the end of the year, about 30

04:19.447 --> 04:25.273
of us was left in the outfit. And so I said, well, 
this is not really what I'm looking for. I mean, I

04:27.335 --> 04:28.496
came to study. I didn't feel I needed all this 
exorbitant discipline. But we couldn't study. We

04:32.900 --> 04:33.501
couldn't eat. I went home. They thought I was some 
kind of a refugee. I lost weight. I wasn't that

04:37.885 --> 04:39.127
heavy to begin with. My hair was cut short. I looked 
like I had come out of Huntsville. So

04:43.733 --> 04:49.159
I said, well, I don't need this. And since the Corps 
was optional, I went ahead and finished out the

04:49.339 --> 04:52.203
year. I felt, OK, I'll finish out my commitment for 
that year that I had agreed to do. And the next year,

04:56.368 --> 04:58.690
I went civilian still. And also, because I had used 
the career days and opportunity to look around,

04:59.711 --> 05:09.082
and I believe in career days for that reason, 
because it did help me to kind of see the

04:59.711 --> 05:09.082
opportunities that were available to me as a 
student here. I did go around all the different

05:09.963 --> 05:12.306
departments that they And when I got to the fourth 
floor of the academic building where the

05:12.826 --> 05:23.542
architecture school used to be, I immediately 
sensed that I could relate to the work and to the

05:12.826 --> 05:23.542
environment and everything else. So I made my 
decision quickly, and I said, okay, that's what

05:23.602 --> 05:27.668
I'm going to do. I'm going to change curriculums 
coming at the end of the school year and when I

05:27.688 --> 05:31.794
enroll for the next year. Who was the dean? Yeah, I 
guess an interesting anecdote. I was counsel. I

05:36.849 --> 05:40.733
had to go through counseling because I was just 
barely scraping by with a C average. And the

05:41.554 --> 05:49.063
counselor, after they did all the testing and 
everything else, told me that I had no aptitude for

05:41.554 --> 05:49.063
architecture and anything related to the field. 
But interesting enough, the following year, I was

05:49.784 --> 05:52.848
a distinguished student. My grade points shot up 
very high. And I managed to get on the dean's list as

05:55.671 --> 05:58.134
a distinguished student. And from there on, it was 
fine. I enjoyed the program and everything else. I

06:02.843 --> 06:06.087
really felt that I was doing what I wanted to do. And 
then during that year, we had various people

06:06.667 --> 06:11.893
visiting lectures that came to the university. It 
was a good lecture program. We had a good lecture

06:12.914 --> 06:14.035
series. And I met different people from around 
this country. And I got to know other faculty in the

06:17.959 --> 06:20.983
advanced years. I got to know Joe McGraw, who was 
then a design professor, and Professor Edward

06:21.003 --> 06:29.492
Romanek, who was also the director of the design 
studios. And they sort of were, they took me under

06:29.911 --> 06:35.680
their wing so that they could help me along and gave 
me encouragement. And then I got to meet, well, I

06:35.700 --> 06:46.296
visualized myself finishing architecture and 
going to, you know, work actually, work for a firm

06:35.700 --> 06:46.296
and going to architectural practice and 
hopefully eventually get my license and all that

06:35.700 --> 06:46.296
business. But during the last year or so, I then got 
interested, of course, in teaching and they

06:54.953 --> 06:57.817
Professor Ramegan-McGraw encouraged me if I 
would be interested in teaching. They needed some

06:57.837 --> 06:59.879
faculty, so I taught for three years. And during 
that time, they had some guest speakers. And one of

07:03.123 --> 07:06.808
them was Reginald Isaacs from Harvard. And he had 
been in South America and was on his way back to

07:07.468 --> 07:14.557
Harvard when they had asked him if he would lecture 
here. So he came and lectured at A&M at the time. And

07:17.381 --> 07:19.583
so we visited and we talked. And so he indicated 
that he would be interested in my applying at

07:20.304 --> 07:24.049
Harvard. in planning. And so I did that later, and I 
was accepted. And so after working for one summer

07:29.440 --> 07:38.194
at Caudill Rowland Scott, and actually worked 
with Bill Caudill that particular summer, it was

07:29.440 --> 07:38.194
an interesting experience in itself. Great guy. I 
really enjoyed working with him, and he was really

07:39.175 --> 07:42.380
an inspiration. I then came back and taught for two 
years at A&M, and then applied at Harvard, and got

07:42.680 --> 07:50.132
accepted, and went for two years in the graduate 
planning program. I got my master's in city

07:51.033 --> 07:52.816
planning there. What year? That was in 62, went 
from 62 to 1964. I taught from 60 to 62, I'm sorry,

07:59.501 --> 08:03.045
here in architecture. Then I worked in Houston the 
summer of 1960, and I worked in Harold Hamilton's

08:03.065 --> 08:11.034
office in Dallas in the summer of 63. So then in, I'm 
sorry, in 1961. Then in 1962, and then I went to

08:15.218 --> 08:18.322
Harvard until 64. And there I got a job. I'm sorry, 
well, after I finish, rather, I interviewed some

08:21.927 --> 08:29.578
people from California and had gotten a job, 
actually a job offer. I interviewed with a firm

08:29.618 --> 08:37.610
representative from a firm in San Francisco, 
Warneke, John Carl Warneke's firm. He had been out

08:37.630 --> 08:40.695
to the East Coast and was interviewing at 
different schools. And so I was introduced to him.

08:43.004 --> 08:45.548
That's interesting, because I was working in his 
office. Really? Yeah. Well, they were setting up a

08:46.789 --> 08:51.936
planning department, actually, within the 
architecture firm at the time, and they needed

08:46.789 --> 08:51.936
somebody to help them set it up. They left their 
libraries and their expertise in planning. So I

08:56.142 --> 09:07.358
did, and we got off well, and so I got everything 
packed, and I took off, went home to see my parents,

08:56.142 --> 09:07.358
and then I drove in a little Ford Falcon all the way 
to California in the middle of the hottest summer I

09:07.523 --> 09:10.066
can imagine. When we hit Southern California, it 
was 110 or 120 degrees, something like that.

09:14.713 --> 09:16.595
Anyway, I survived the trip and got to California. 
But when I got to San Francisco, this gentleman I

09:16.615 --> 09:23.425
had interviewed with told me, I have a very 
interesting job assignment for you. And so I said,

09:23.705 --> 09:24.927
let's talk about it. So I did. I had got myself 
checked in. And he wanted to send me to Hawaii. And I

09:30.541 --> 09:32.363
said, well, I don't know. I said, I was interested 
in coming out to California, because I've heard so

09:32.443 --> 09:35.407
much about California. I wanted to really get to 
know California, San Francisco area, the whole

09:35.427 --> 09:39.612
stadium. So I wasn't too keen on that. So I managed 
to contact, I was kind of in the process of making an

09:41.494 --> 09:50.225
arrangement to ship my car and everything to 
Hawaii. And I just, by luck, happened to call a

09:50.765 --> 10:00.497
former professor of mine, Professor Joseph J. 
McGraw, who at the time had also, before that even

09:50.765 --> 10:00.497
had gone to California, was working in 
California. And I sort of kept some

10:00.967 --> 10:05.473
correspondence with him, and I just thought I'd 
say hello and see how he was doing. And so he said,

10:06.234 --> 10:09.538
well, what are you doing out here on the West Coast? 
I said, I didn't realize you were interested in

10:09.558 --> 10:11.401
coming out to the West Coast. He said, well, I 
wasn't either. I just sort of thought I would. And

10:14.325 --> 10:25.219
so he started telling me what he was doing, who he 
was working with in this fairly large firm in the

10:14.325 --> 10:25.219
Bay Area, and that there were native people, and 
that if I was interested in working for their firm,

10:25.486 --> 10:27.089
I could have a job, you know. And so he offered me a 
position in their firm. And he explained the kind

10:29.493 --> 10:30.915
of work that the firm did. It was an architecture, 
engineering, and planning firm. And so I said,

10:33.519 --> 10:34.881
well, I don't know. I have to check with these 
people first because I already made my

10:34.901 --> 10:38.027
commitments to them. So once I could not change 
them, he gave me an assignment in San Francisco

10:38.047 --> 10:43.956
office, in Wernicke's office. I decided then to go 
with, at the time, it was Woolsey, Hamm, and Blair,

10:43.976 --> 10:52.270
fairly large firm in California. And I started 
working on a Sunday afternoon. They were so busy at

10:55.691 --> 10:56.733
the time. California was an incredibly busy state 
at the time. That was 1962? This was in 1964. Right.

11:03.663 --> 11:05.465
At Foster City. In 1964, the firm had built the 
first building in the new town called Foster City,

11:05.485 --> 11:15.620
which was sort of an invention building into the 
Bay Area. It had been approved, of course, and so

11:15.640 --> 11:17.062
forth. By Jack Foster from Texas. Yes. Yes, I 
didn't realize his origin. That's where we met.

11:24.516 --> 11:24.916
That's right. We were working with William Blair, 
and it was an interesting operation because we

11:25.117 --> 11:35.551
had, I think, a very unique setup of planners, 
engineers, architects working together in

11:25.117 --> 11:35.551
interdisciplinary teams, which I have believed 
in. See, Joe McGraw was there, and Jim Gardner. Did

11:42.521 --> 11:43.682
he arrive later? I'm not quite sure. Jim, I think, 
arrived later, yeah. And Matt Copenhaver. Matt

11:50.722 --> 11:51.928
Copenhaver was there. Dick Ehrenberger was 
there. Let's see who else did we play. Well, that's

11:59.378 --> 12:02.242
enough talent for one firm. It was a very 
interesting group, actually. And the

12:04.225 --> 12:11.535
development design department, which we called 
3D department, was an interesting department

12:04.225 --> 12:11.535
because we brought all these people together into 
a team. And we did the preliminary work and the

12:11.555 --> 12:15.380
selling of the studies to clients. And then the 
preliminary concepts were hammered out by this

12:16.081 --> 12:18.865
group. And then they were passed on to the other 
individuals for the surveying and the actual

12:18.905 --> 12:26.135
engineering and cost estimates and so forth. So it 
made for an interesting combination. After

12:28.606 --> 12:44.502
having been with the firm for actually, I guess it 
was less than a year, they decided to encourage me

12:28.606 --> 12:44.502
to continue with the firm by giving me a bonus at the 
end of the year, which they seldom gave to anybody

12:28.606 --> 12:44.502
who was with the firm less than a year. And the guys 
said they were in a real quandary about it. So I felt

12:47.045 --> 12:48.246
good about that. I felt I wanted to continue with 
this firm. And they, in fact, gave me more

12:49.767 --> 12:53.171
responsibilities and larger assignments. I got 
to work on the Southside's plan with it for the big

12:55.015 --> 13:03.253
developer, Dolger, Mr. Dolger, who had done 
basically built all of that stuff. South San

13:03.757 --> 13:04.518
Francisco. South San Francisco area after the 
war, which made the Tiki-Taki house famous. He's

13:09.465 --> 13:10.967
the guy who actually built them. You had a hand in 
that. No, I did not have a hand in the Tiki-Takis. I

13:14.993 --> 13:19.619
did have an interesting experience meeting the 
man, because he was a very interesting fellow,

13:14.993 --> 13:19.619
actually. He was a very down-to-earth guy, and he 
felt that he was meeting and addressing a need that

13:19.719 --> 13:29.713
wasn't being met by anybody else for low- and 
middle-income families, especially after the

13:19.719 --> 13:29.713
war when there was an with a high shortage of 
housing. And one of his policies, an interesting

13:32.436 --> 13:43.590
one that he had at the time he was building houses in 
South San Francisco area was that he would put a

13:32.436 --> 13:43.590
tree in front of every house as a minimum in the 
landscaping and so forth. So we went back and drove

13:43.730 --> 13:46.574
around this area. And it really looked kind of 
decent, even though it was kind of high density.

13:50.499 --> 13:52.621
Houses were packed in kind of tight, to be sure. But 
he had kept up a fairly attractive quality

13:53.282 --> 13:59.650
development after all. In the new area that we were 
working in, the 25,000 acre that we were working

14:00.085 --> 14:11.702
with him now, that was definitely a quality 
development, and he wanted that, and he wanted to

14:00.085 --> 14:11.702
set a good standard, and it was a beautiful area of 
the county. How long were you with Woolsey

14:12.082 --> 14:13.825
Hammond, Blair? Well, I was there in the area about 
a year and a half, and then at the end of 1965, they

14:13.845 --> 14:25.502
had gotten some assignments in South America, and 
they had put some teams together to send When the

14:26.056 --> 14:28.639
projects came in, they didn't have anybody to 
send. Everybody backed out. They didn't want to go

14:30.341 --> 14:31.722
for some reason or another. Yeah, so then I had the 
opportunity of my life. The vice president said

14:36.587 --> 14:43.515
they needed to send someone to take care of some 
very substantial projects in Chile. There was a

14:44.736 --> 14:51.163
program, actually, by the Chilean government to 
start planning in the country, establish

14:44.736 --> 14:51.163
planning in the country. They were doing national 
planning, regional planning, and local

14:51.864 --> 14:55.067
planning. And our job was to develop the local 
planning end of it. And in order to do national

14:58.680 --> 15:10.983
planning, they felt they needed to have more 
information at the local level in order to bring

14:58.680 --> 15:10.983
together all the plans and therefore use those to 
put together the national budgets for different

14:58.680 --> 15:10.983
categories of investments. I think that I had left 
and had taken a leave of absence from the firm

15:11.083 --> 15:18.237
before you left for Chile. and had gone with the 
Association of Bay Area Governments. That's

15:22.091 --> 15:22.351
right. You were in transition to go to Association 
of Bay Area Governments. That was all because of my

15:25.935 --> 15:27.496
thesis. Oh, really? Which was on regional 
planning in the Bay Area. I see. Well, that was

15:31.740 --> 15:33.922
certainly the place to go at the time. Yeah, it was a 
good move. Yeah, it was an impressive operation at

15:36.125 --> 15:46.975
AIPAC, and I had a little knowledge of it, of 
course, because we had to do some relating our own

15:36.125 --> 15:46.975
local planning in the area, and we were very 
conscious of what they were trying to do.

15:47.377 --> 15:50.309
coordinate the whole Bay region was an impressive 
project. And to this day, it seems to be an

15:50.409 --> 15:52.859
impressive effort. We had pretty good support 
from the federal government. Oh, yes. It was a big

15:56.594 --> 15:57.859
effort. I think certainly that also led to the 
creation of the Association of Bay Area

15:58.615 --> 16:07.432
Governments, of course, which brought unity 
between county cities and the state. A lot of

16:08.174 --> 16:10.498
large-scale projects had to be coordinated at 
that level. It couldn't be done otherwise without

16:10.558 --> 16:12.041
that agency. I think it created an awareness of the 
area as a region, which resulted in the Bay

16:12.402 --> 16:19.476
Conservation and Development Commission. I was 
going to say, that then was a follow-up with the

16:19.456 --> 16:23.361
Conservation Commission. And the California 
Coastal Zone Commission. Right. And that was also

16:26.424 --> 16:35.635
forerunners of many of the coastal zone 
management and large area management, regional

16:26.424 --> 16:35.635
management programs we have since come to know. 
Well, back to Chile. You were down there, and how

16:37.016 --> 16:39.319
long were you in Chile? Well, I was there for two and 
a half years. Two and a half years. And you finished

16:42.002 --> 16:45.246
your work, and then you came back to Wolseyham and 
Blair? After I finished the work there, they

16:45.466 --> 16:48.670
wanted me to come back to the... San Francisco 
office, San Mateo office. But at the time, I had

16:53.088 --> 16:58.796
been in correspondence with Professor McGraw, 
who had expressed an interest in my coming back. He

16:59.217 --> 17:06.528
had left Wilson, Hammond, Blair, I believe, about 
a year before I left to go to Chile, approximately.

